2. **The "Glass Ceiling" Effect in SEN Categories**: By comparing progression rates of students with different SEN provisions, this research identifies the specific threshold where academic support transitions from enabling access to HE to enabling access to high-tariff institutions. It seeks to quantify the "conversion efficiency" of SEN support across the prestige spectrum.

3. **Temporal Sensitivity to Policy Shifts**: This study maps the inflection points in the progression gap against major legislative changes in UK higher education funding and admissions policy over the last 14 years. It aims to determine which policy eras were most effective at narrowing the high-tariff gap versus the general access gap.

4. **The Intersectionality of Ethnicity and Socio-Economic Status**: This research isolates the progression rates of specific ethnic groups within the most disadvantaged POLAR quintiles to identify "resilience patterns." It aims to highlight which ethnic sub-groups show higher-than-expected progression rates despite structural socio-economic barriers.

5. **Stability vs. Volatility in Disadvantage Metrics**: This study compares the year-on-year volatility of progression rates across different demographic dimensions (e.g., Sex vs. Looked After Status). It tests the hypothesis that certain socio-economic categories are more sensitive to macro-economic or societal disruptions than others.

6. **The "High-Tariff" Concentration Index**: Rather than just measuring gaps, this study treats the distribution of high-tariff students as a spatial and demographic concentration problem. It calculates the Gini coefficient of high-tariff access across all categories to identify which groups are the most underrepresented relative to their cohort size.

7. **Progression Divergence Post-2019**: This study specifically isolates the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic years on the trajectory of the HE access gap. It tests whether the disruption accelerated or reversed long-term trends in equity for both general and high-tariff progression.

8. **Relative vs. Absolute Equity Gaps**: This research explores the mathematical relationship between the percentage-point gap and the ratio of progression rates. It seeks to define a standardized "Equity Disparity Index" that remains stable regardless of the overall increase in university participation rates.

9. **The "First Language" Barrier in Selective HE**: This study investigates the progression gap specifically for students with English as an Additional Language (EAL). It aims to determine if language status acts as a greater barrier for entry into high-tariff institutions compared to general HE, controlling for other disadvantage indicators.

10. **Predictive Parity Modeling**: By fitting non-linear growth models to the 14-year dataset, this study projects the "Year of Parity" for each disadvantaged group. It identifies which specific characteristics are currently on a trajectory to reach equitable representation in high-tariff institutions within the next decade and which remain stagnant.
\end{IDEAS}


